observations.recommendation:
We recommended the management to:
•Submit the distribution sheet in relation to the goods under Check No. 86850969;
•Submit Authorization letters or Certification that goods were properly dispensed with relating to consolidated receipts (same signature or signed “for”) of goods;
•Submit acknowledgement receipts of the recipients who did not sign the distribution sheets;
•Substantiate the “Not Found” recipients;
•Justify the lack of data with regard quantity, kind/type, and, etc.;
•Ensure that subsequent programs have program designs that indicate the kind and quantity of goods to be distributed to different recipients and the reason for such an arrangement;
•Prospectively, ensure that all line items in the Purchase Order are tagged with brand names; and
•Advise the focal persons of these types of programs to closely coordinate with the Accounting Office to ensure that records are properly updated.

We recommended management to:

1.Issue Demand Letters to fast track liquidation and/or refund of the fund transfers;
2.Revise the Memorandum of Agreement (MOAs) to include a duration within which the proposed project should be implemented, and the funds utilized for prospective financial Assistance grants to avoid delaying of project implementation; 
3.Add penal clauses in the MOAs for financial assistance to safeguard downloaded funds; and
4.Monitor the projects under financial assistance of the LGU diligently

We recommended to the management the following actions:

1.Write a collection letter to separated officials and re-establish payment terms of outstanding cash advances via a notarized agreement;
2.Prohibit the clearance of employees with pending accountabilities especially if the terminal leave benefits are not sufficient to cover the outstanding accountabilities or create a separate agreement or understanding between the LGU and the outgoing individual(s) to oblige them to pay the remaining balance of the cash advances net of terminal leave benefits even after their separation/clearance from the LGU;
3.Ensure that cash advances are liquidated after their specific purposes are consummated; and
4.Avoid the grant of additional cash advances if the official or employee still has a pending cash advance for liquidation.
Otherwise, if the outgoing individual/s refuse to pay their outstanding accountabilities, then the official/s who cleared him/her should shoulder the outstanding balance of cash advances of the separated employees as a consequence for their negligence.

We recommended to require its Accounting Office staff to coordinate with Al Amanah Islamic Bank for the immediate reconciliation of the noted variance on the recorded balance of the Loans Payable account. Reconciling items should be adjusted immediately to bring both records into agreement;

To require reconciliation of records to be conducted at least once a year of all the loan accounts of the LGU; and

To require the Accounting Office staff to maintain separate record for each loan account.

Recommendation/s:
We recommended management to:
Assess the line items under the Land Account and consider possible adjusting entries, if warranted;
Consider processing the deeds of donation of land properties that the management intends to donate to other government agencies;
Furnish the accounting office with copies of the deeds of donation to allow proper derecognition of asset accounts; and
Ensure that transactions are recorded based on their actual use and/or purpose consistent with IPSAS and COA Circular No. 2015-009.

Recommendation/s:
We recommended management to:
Submit justification for the lackluster collection efforts with time-bound management strategy plans to boost collection from the vendees of the Paglaum Project;
Issue time-bound notarized final demand letters to vendees with unpaid amortization of at least three (3) consecutive monthly installments;
Consider the remedies provided under Item 2-Terms of the Conditional Contract to Sell for the resistant vendees who refuse to respect their payment obligations;
Ensure that proper screening and profiling are done prior to assigning a collector (not related to any vendees/beneficiaries within the 4th degree of consanguinity or affinity) for the Paglaum Project to avoid any conflict of interest;
Assign a focal person responsible for updating the individual records of the vendees of the Paglaum Projects in the offices of the MEEDO and the Accounting department;
Instruct the Accounting department and the MEEDO to conduct monthly reconciliation of records of vendees;
Instruct the Accounting department to submit their basis for recording the collections under Other payables;
Instruct the Accounting and MEEDO to evaluate and consider the Per Audit Amortization Schedule and update their records as needed; and
Advise the accounting department to establish a receivable balance for the due and demandable amortization payments and interest.

Recommendation/s:
We recommended management to:
Submit the lacking documents relevant to the grant and proper liquidation of the out-of-country traveling expenses to allow completion of the audit evaluation;
Submit JEV No. 100-24-07-GJ137 and its supporting documents;
Furnish the audit office with the authorities to travel to Paris, France, from the Provincial Governor and DILG Region X Regional Director. Otherwise, justify the necessity and regularity of the travel to Paris, France, without proper authorities from DILG Region X and the Provincial Governor for evaluation of the regularity of the transaction;
Submit an explanation/justification on the following:
The lack of invitation of the host organization (The Hague Academy, Netherlands) on September 2-3 & 6-10, 2024;
Discrepancy between the confirmed dates of events in the travel to USA vis-à-vis the actual travel period indicated in the Itinerary of travel.
The different registration costs in the VLMP Message transmission (P160,000) as compared with the Itinerary of Travel and the Official Receipt of the VLMP (P80,000.00);
Evaluate the accounting entries for adjustment, if necessary; and
Ensure that succeeding out-of-country travels are duly authorized and should strictly adhere to existing rules and regulations to avoid possible suspensions or disallowances.

Recommendation/s:
We recommended that the management submit the following:
Documentary proof that these recipients are not 4Ps beneficiaries and/or government employees regardless of status;
Documentary proof that Claimant Nos. 11 & 12; 13 & 14; and 24 & 25, are not members of one family despite having same last names;
Valid IDs and TUPAD IDs;
Proof of receipt of the required worker’s profiles and RCI/ROD and its supporting documents by DOLE on or before December 20, 2023;
Affidavit of oneness of Claimant #2 stating that the one who signed the Payroll, Contract of Service and Attendance are one and the same despite having the different signatures;
Justification why Claimant # 17 was allowed to participate in the TUPAD program despite being under 18 years of age; and
Detailed list of expenditures relating to the material support of LGU Lantapan totaling P93,400.00.
We further recommended to management that subsequent project implementations of these types of initiatives strictly abide to their corresponding guidelines and Memorandum of Agreement.

Recommendation/s:
We recommended that the management submit the following lacking documents:
Supplemental List of Eligible beneficiaries for those who received social pension but did not appear in the existing list of beneficiaries;
Justification for the lack of signatures of the authorized representative and witnesses in the authorization letters;
Copies of Valid IDs/OSCA ID/Birth Certificates of claimants;
Copies of Valid IDs/OSCA ID/Birth Certificates of authorized representatives;
Copies of Valid IDs/OSCA ID/Birth Certificates of authorized nearest surviving relative;
Warranty and Release from liability signed by the authorized representative (for death of beneficiaries);
RCI, ROD and Fund Utilization Report;
Accomplishment report from LGU Lantapan;
Monitoring Report for the beneficiaries that were added in or removed from the payroll as compared to the certified list of eligible beneficiaries;
Social Pension Update Form & Utilization Template;
Copy of the signed payroll for those who failed to sign;
Justification of the different signatures in the Valid ID/Authorization Letter as compared to the Payroll (If the claim was received via proxy, Authorization letter with the signature of the beneficiary, authorized representative, and witness and the valid ID of the authorized representative should be submitted. Otherwise, if they are from the one person, the Affidavit of Oneness should be executed.);
Affidavit of Oneness for the misspelt names of one individual;
For those who used both signature and thumbmark across key documents, justification as to why the recipient did not consistently sign the document should be submitted;
Justification as why 17 individuals appearing in the certified list of beneficiaries did not receive their social pension; and
Justification for the late distribution and liquidation of the Social Pension.
In addition to the required submissions above, we also recommended that, for the succeeding Senior Citizen Social Pension Programs, the disbursing officer should be provided with a copy of the Memorandum of Agreement and the corresponding guideline to inform the said officer of his/her responsibility.
Otherwise, the LGU could also opt to bond the MSWDO or an eligible staff in the MSWD Office to enable them to function as disbursing officer, considering that this program is under their direct supervision, and they are much more acquainted with their rules and regulations.

Recommendation/s:
We recommended management to:
Establish reorder points for all inventories particularly on high-demand goods (i.e. medicines, medical supplies, etc.) via resolution or executive order to mitigate rushed purchases of inventory;
Fortify inventory management system by creating a feasible and efficient process flow and assigning additional staff/s to update inventory records per office;
Provide necessary tools and equipment (i.e. computers) for inventory management personnel; and
Ensure that procurement planning and execution activities of the LGU are properly implemented and considers timing activities, volume of demand, procurement timelines, availability of goods, etc.

Recommendation/s:
We recommended the following to the management:
Submit a written justification regarding the issues cited for further evaluation;
Remind the budget officer to re-acquaint herself with the 20% LDF utilization guidelines for all succeeding transactions;
Endeavor to charge the remaining unpaid balance of the project against the General Fund-Proper (Capital Outlay); and
Stop charging expenditures not aligning with the 20% LDF utilization guidelines.

We recommended the following to management:

•Transition to the Imprest system and follow the correct accounting treatment for Petty Cash-related Transactions;
•Instruct the petty cash custodian to establish a cut-off yearly so that he is given an ample time to liquidate the Petty Cash Fund at the end of the year;
•Follow the PCV template as mandated under the LTOM and have the requestor sign the PCV in Box A (Requested by); and
•Delegate the duty of approving Petty Cash requests to the immediate supervisors as required under the LTOM and revise the Petty Cash Fund Policy to include detailed process flow, control, and accountability guidelines.

We recommended to the management to do the following:

1. Create the SB ordinances fortifying the existence of their LEEs;
2. Ensure the preparation of Annual Operating Budgets for LEEs using its respective estimated/projected income relating to its operations; 
3. Stop charging Personal Services (PS) and Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses (MOOE) relating to the local economic enterprises against the General Fund Budgets;
4. Conduct a feasibility study and assess the sustainability of the Local Economic Enterprises; and
5. Maintain separate books for LEEs as noted in the NGAS Manual for transactions relating to the operations of the LEEs;

Otherwise, if in case the LGU determines that the LEEs are no longer feasible, we recommended that the LGU should absorb the enterprises, particularly the Public Market & the Terminal, in the general fund under a certain office/department as among its priority services and not as local economic enterprises under a separate office. (Underscored for emphasis)

